WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:04.445
Respiratory distress syndrome in the
newborn, also called neonatal RDS,

2
00:00:04.824 --> 00:00:08.444
is one of the most critical conditions
you'll manage as a respiratory therapist in

3
00:00:08.444 --> 00:00:09.284
the NICU.

4
00:00:09.585 --> 00:00:12.524
And at its core, this disease is all about
one

5
00:00:12.524 --> 00:00:14.685
problem, not enough surfactant.

6
00:00:15.484 --> 00:00:19.065
Surfactant normally reduces surface
tension in the alveoli, allowing them

7
00:00:19.065 --> 00:00:20.745
to stay open during exhalation.

8
00:00:20.944 --> 00:00:24.385
But in premature infants, surfactant
production is insufficient.

9
00:00:24.645 --> 00:00:25.704
So what happens?

10
00:00:25.924 --> 00:00:27.225
The alveoli collapse.

11
00:00:27.545 --> 00:00:31.325
This leads to decreased lung compliance,
increased work of breathing,

12
00:00:31.725 --> 00:00:33.325
and widespread atelectasis.

13
00:00:34.005 --> 00:00:36.744
As the lungs collapse, gas exchange
becomes impaired.

14
00:00:37.544 --> 00:00:39.924
Oxygenation drops, carbon dioxide can
rise,

15
00:00:40.185 --> 00:00:44.264
and the infant begins to show signs of
respiratory distress such as tachypnea,

16
00:00:44.764 --> 00:00:46.705
nasal flaring, grunting, and retractions.

17
00:00:47.145 --> 00:00:48.185
That grunting you hear?

18
00:00:48.525 --> 00:00:52.625
It's the baby trying to create intrinsic
peep to keep the alveoli open.

19
00:00:52.625 --> 00:00:57.104
From a diagnostic standpoint, you'll often
see a classic ground-

20
00:00:57.104 --> 00:00:59.944
glass appearance on chest X-ray, along
with low lung

21
00:00:59.944 --> 00:01:00.404
volumes.

22
00:01:01.165 --> 00:01:04.525
Blood gases may initially show hypoxemia,
and as fatigue sets

23
00:01:04.525 --> 00:01:07.584
in, rising carbon dioxide becomes a major
red flag.

24
00:01:08.364 --> 00:01:09.385
Here's the clinical connection.

25
00:01:09.864 --> 00:01:12.285
This is not just a lung problem, it's a
compliance

26
00:01:12.285 --> 00:01:12.705
problem.

27
00:01:13.065 --> 00:01:15.565
The stiffer the lungs, the harder the
infant has to

28
00:01:15.565 --> 00:01:16.245
work to breathe.

29
00:01:16.464 --> 00:01:20.245
And without intervention, that workload
leads to rapid fatigue and

30
00:01:20.245 --> 00:01:22.065
potential respiratory failure.

31
00:01:22.785 --> 00:01:25.985
Management is focused on one goal, keeping
alveolite open.

32
00:01:26.605 --> 00:01:30.285
That means applying CPAP early to provide
continuous positive pressure,

33
00:01:31.125 --> 00:01:32.724
improving functional residual capacity.

34
00:01:33.544 --> 00:01:36.485
If distress worsens, you may need to
escalate to mechanical

35
00:01:36.485 --> 00:01:36.985
ventilation.

36
00:01:37.944 --> 00:01:40.805
One of the most important therapies is
surfactant replacement.

37
00:01:41.404 --> 00:01:45.385
Administered via an endotracheal tube,
this directly addresses the root

38
00:01:45.385 --> 00:01:48.944
cause and can dramatically improve lung
compliance and oxygenation.

39
00:01:49.745 --> 00:01:50.504
Board Prep Tip.

40
00:01:51.245 --> 00:01:55.605
Always associate neonatal RGS with
prematurity, surfactant deficiency,

41
00:01:56.305 --> 00:01:59.625
decreased compliance, and the need for
CPAP or surfactant therapy.

42
00:02:00.364 --> 00:02:02.444
And as the RT, your role is critical.

43
00:02:03.084 --> 00:02:05.824
Monitoring work of breathing, oxygenation,
ventilatory

44
00:02:05.824 --> 00:02:08.464
status, and response to therapy in real
time.

45
00:02:09.104 --> 00:02:12.705
Recognizing early deterioration, like
increasing oxygen needs,

46
00:02:13.024 --> 00:02:15.445
worsening retractions, or rising carbon
dioxide,

47
00:02:15.585 --> 00:02:19.164
can make the difference between
stabilization and rapid decline.

48
00:02:20.024 --> 00:02:23.505
Bottom line, neonatal RDS is a surfactant
problem that becomes

49
00:02:23.505 --> 00:02:24.524
a ventilation problem.

50
00:02:25.085 --> 00:02:27.845
Your job is to support the lungs, reduce
the work

51
00:02:27.845 --> 00:02:30.705
of breathing, and intervene before fatigue
sets in.

